			 @{b}USER ' S MANUAL  OF  @{fg HIGHLIGHT}EXECUTE@{fg TEXT}  VERSION  1.0@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

  This tool intend to be an efficient replacement for the built-in Workbench
  Execute command. Please read carefully this manual, especially section
  "Commands", because this tool provides a lot of hidden and useful functions.


  @{"   1.INTRODUCTION   " link Introduction }	Why this piece of software

  @{"   2.REQUIREMENTS   " link Requirements }	Before to install it

  @{"   3.COMMANDS       " link Usage }	How to use it

  @{"   4.REFERENCE      " link Reference }	Command line reference

  @{"   5.SOURCES        " link Sources }	Some notes about sources

@endnode
@node Introduction

			______________
			 @{b}INTRODUCTION@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

  Execute menu entry of Workbench is a very good idea, but suffers of severe
  restrictions that make this utility almost unusable. Among unfriendliness:
	* No multitasking! What a shame! Therefore...
	* Can't use drag and drop
	* No help for spelling very long and boring filename
	* Doesn't remember previous command (like in standard CON: window)
	* Keyboard support very limited
	* Can't use this utility into another environment (ie: everywhere)

  Well the goal of my utility is no more that providing the power of a
  shell like KingCON: into a single window with a simple text gadget.

  This utility isn't as simple as it seems. Like I said, it exists several
  hidden features, that you may discover by reading this manual, to have a
  efficient replacement, and not just a simple and ugly remake.

@endnode
@node Requirements "The requirements before to start"

			_____________________________
			 @{b}REQUIREMENTS BEFORE TO START@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

  Nothing, or almost. An amiga with ROM 2.1 or more will be suffisant.
  External libraries like ASL.library for inserting filenames can be
  useful but not required and of course, locale.library for internationa-
  lization support.

  To install this tool, simply put the program (with or without it's icon)
  somewhere into your path.

  To get the best efficiency of this tool, I strongly recommend to launch it
  from starter program, like ToolManager or MCP. As this utility @{b}is not@{ub} an
  Amiga commodity, there is no way to put it into background. Note that it
  will be clever enough to see if it's already running. In such case, both
  copy will just quit.

@endnode
@node Usage "User's manual of Execute"

			___________________
			       @{b}USAGE@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ


  @{fg HIGHLIGHT}1.Getting started@{fg TEXT}

  To run this tool, just double-click on its icon or enter its name into a
  shell. A window will be poped up into the current active screen (not neces-
  sary public), which will look very closer to the workbench `Execute' menu.
  The string gadget has been a little bit extended to give more ease to key
  in commands. Follow the guide...

  @{fg HIGHLIGHT}2.Extra features@{fg TEXT}

  First, as this is a simple task, it will never freeze your workbench, thus
  you can @{b}drag'n drop icon@{ub} from this latter: the fully qualified filename
  will be inserted at current cursor position, @{b}enclosing it with quotes@{ub} if it
  contains spaces.

  Another thing, particularly boring to add is the @{b}NIL: redirection@{ub} for shutting
  down boring output of some commands. In normal days you have to put somewhere
  in your path the string ">NIL:", which is quite annoying. Now you just have to
  uncheck menu entry "Output window" and both standard Input and Output will be
  definitively closed. Notice that @{b}menu shortcuts work even if string gadget is
  activated@{ub}. Of course, in order to help you remember whether redirection is
  enabled, a marker (<>NIL:) will be indicated in the title bar. Note that this
  can still be overridden using command line parameters.

  Another piece of useful information, is the @{b}current working directory@{ub}. The full
  path is shown in the title bar. Notice that if you specify a directory name as
  a command to execute, the program will just @{b}change its current working directory@{ub}.

  If there is one thing particularly boring to enter, it's of course filename.
  Common problems are numerous, among annoyingness there are the lack of ASL
  support, or worst, AmigaDOS wildcards, spelling of very long object's name
  is very irritating, obliging generally user to do bad compromise between
  shortness and meaningness of filenames, like on so many systems.

  Well, it's time to have efficient solutions. This tool provide a lot of way for
  enterring path. The simplest is to use @{b}ASL requester@{ub}. By pressing @{b}Amiga+L@{ub}, you
  just have to select your filenames and they will be inserted, separated with
  one space, and of course enclosed with quotes if one path contains space.

  Another quick way for automaticly enter group of filenames, is to use @{b}AmigaDOS
  wildcards@{ub}. That's also particularly useful when command doesn't support wild-
  cards, you just type your wildcard and by pressing @{b}Amiga+M@{ub}, it will be expanded
  to all objects it represents, just like if you choose them using ASL requester.
  Notice that by holding down Shift qualifier, only @{b}file name@{ub} will be
  expanded. To expand only @{b}macthing directories@{ub}, you can use @{b}Amiga+P@{ub}.
  If no object has matched, the screen will flash.

  Another way to show pattern-expanding results, is to use the @{b}Tab@{ub} key. The pattern
  before the cursor will be expanded, like Amiga-M, but if more than one match is
  found, they will be displayed in a listview gadget, enabling you to choose one
  entry. Note that, if you don't gave a pattern, "#?" will be automaticly added
  at the end of your path. Notice that @{b}Shift-Tab@{ub} will expand just matching
  files, and @{b}Ctrl-Tab@{ub}, just directories.

  Last but not least, this tool can manage a @{b}review buffer@{ub} of enterred commands,
  just like a shell. You can therefore browse through this buffer using up and
  down cursor key, to get respectively the previous and the next command in this
  buffer. But like so, it wouldn't be very useful as buffer will be lost once the
  program has exited. That's why it's possible to store buffer content into a
  @{b}preference file@{ub}.

  By default the preference file will be stored into "S:Shell-History", but you
  can easily change using command line argument (see @{" Command line arguments " link CLI}).
  There is two ways for updating this file: either you do to it yourself, by
  pressing @{b}Shift-Return@{ub} for executing your command, or you just let the program
  save your settings whenever they are changed, using @{b}AUTOSAVE@{ub} keyword from
  command line. Actually Shift-Return will @{b}temporarly revert@{ub} saving policy.

  Notice that, unlike the shell, this tool will eliminate all duplicates, whatever
  the case they are. The preference file is a simple ASCII text format. Therefore,
  you can edit it by hand, to remove for example undesired command.

@endnode
@node Reference

			_______________________
			       @{b}REFERENCE@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

  Here are summarize all command supported by this tool. First, here follows
  extended features that support the string gadget:

	@{b}Shortcut	Description@{ub}
	ESC		Like `Cancel' button
	Shift+Enter	Revert saving policy
	Amiga+O		Toggle Output window on/off
	Amiga+I		Take care or not of ".info" in filename completition
	Amiga+L		Open an ASL requester to insert one or more files
	Amiga+M		Expand pattern located BEFORE cursor
	Amiga+Shift+M	Expand only files that match with pattern
	Amiga+P		Ditto with directories
	Cursor Up/Down	Browse through review buffer
	Shift Up/Down   Search for prev/next command with same prefix
	Tab		Complete filename with any matching objects
	Shift Tab	Complete filename with files only
	Ctrl Tab	Complete directory name

  This tool can accept some arguments (command line only), here is the exhaustiv
  list of accepted keywords:

	@{b}Keyword		Description@{ub}
	GEOMETRY	Position and width of main window (height is auto-computed).
			This is a comma-separated list of 3 signed numbers. First
			two represent window position (if negativ, relative to
			right or bottom border of screen), last one represent
			window width, relative to screen if negativ. Default geometry
			is ",,400", which center window in the middle of screen.

	OUTWIN		Ditto for possible output window: up to 4 numbers can be
			specified (last one is for window height). Default geometry
			is ",,-100,200", which center a window of 100 pixels less
			than screen's width and 200 pixels high.

	AUTOSAVE	Auto save review buffer if it is modified. By default its
			content is lost once program has finished to execute the
			command.

	HISTORY		Specify a filename to store review history. Default one is
			"S:Shell-History". Be careful to do not add a newline on
			the last line of this file, otherwise it will be considered
			as being an empty command.

	CWD		Specify a directory name to be set as current working dir-
			ectory. By default it uses the directory where it has been
			started.

	NOINFO		Disable at start the "List info files" menu entry. Info
			files will be discarded from pattern expanding, filename
			completition and ASL requester.

	NOOUTPUT	Disable at start output window.

	GUI		Force GUI to appear.

	CMD		Command to execute using current settings. No graphical
			interface will be poped up, unless GUI switch has been
			specified. Note that entire rest of line will be taken
			as the command to execute, redardless of possible known
			switches present after.

@endnode
@node Sources "Notes about sources"

			___________________
			 @{b}ABOUT THE SOURCES@{ub}
			ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

  Sources are given for didactionnal purposes. If someone wants to improve it,
  feel free. The only thing to don't forget is that everything contained in
  this archive is placed under the terms of the GNU Public license, namely
  it's free software and must be stayed like this.

  That was for boring stuff...

  For more fun and if you have a decent C compiler, you can change some hard-
  coded settings of this utility. This parameters are gathered into a single
  C include file, named "Execute.h". Here follows possible values that may be
  adjusted to better conveniance:

	@{b}Keyword		Default value	Description@{ub}
	MAX_COM		256		Size in bytes of string gadget buffer.
	MAX_BUF		1024		Size in bytes of review buffer.
	INSERT_PATH	'l'		Character shortcut for ASL support.
	EXPAND_PAT	'm'		Character for expanding wildcards.
					(Filenames will use Shift'ed one).
	EXPAND_DIR	'p'		Ditto for expanding directories.
	NIL_MARK	"  - <>NIL:"	String added when output disabled

  Notice that shortcut will always be used in conjunction with one of the Amiga
  keys.

  This tools has been successfully compiled with gcc and SAS/C. All you have to
  do is a simple command line like this, to compile it:
	$ gcc #?.c -o Execute -O2 -noixemul -s
  Or, if you prefer SAS/C:
	$ sc #?.c link ign 100 opt pname Execute

@endnode
